  title     = {Augmentative and alternative communication with children with severe/profound intellectual and multiple disabilities: Speech language pathologistsâ€™ clinical practices and reasoning},
  journal   = {Disability and Rehabilitation: Assistive Technology},
  year      = {2022},
  volume    = {19},
  number    = {3},
  month     = {November},
  annote    = { While speech language pathologists are generally highly receptive to and encouraging of assistive technology when dealing with patients with PIMD, the reality of its usage may be more complex. People with PIMD tend to develop at a slow and unpredictable pace, making it notoriously hard to implement general AAC methods. The effectiveness of various AAC are also dependent on their environment: are the parents/caregivers competent in using the assistive technology? How would the patient communicate in an environment where the people around them may not be as competent, particularly in doing everyday tasks? Additionally, the types of AAC that may seem to be more efficient (i.e. visual scene displays) were reported to be less used compared to other, more "cognitively demanding" methods of communication.}
